==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Opal
<hw>O"pal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>opalus</ets>:
cf. Gr. <?/, Skr. <ets>upala</ets> a rock, stone, precious stone: cf. F.
<ets>opale</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral consisting,
like quartz, of silica, but inferior to quartz in hardness and specific
gravity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <stype>precious opal</stype> presents a peculiar
play of colors of delicate tints, and is highly esteemed as a gem. One
kind, with a varied play of color in a reddish ground, is called the
<stype>harlequin opal</stype>. The <stype>fire opal</stype> has colors
like the red and yellow of flame. <stype>Common opal</stype> has a milky
appearance. <stype>Menilite</stype> is a brown impure variety, occurring
in concretions at Menilmontant, near Paris. Other varieties are
<stype>cacholong</stype>, <stype>girasol</stype>,
<stype>hyalite</stype>, and <stype>geyserite</stype>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Opalesce</ent>⟦br⟧
